
[1]bid

   BID, v.t. pret. bid, or bade; pp. bid, bidden. [L. peto, to drive at,
   to attack, to ask, to desire, to beseech, anciently beto; impetus.
   Applied to the voice, it denotes utterance, a driving of sounds, which
   is applied to asking, prayer, and command. Class Bd.]

   1. To ask; to request; to invite.

   Go ye into the highways, and as many as ye shall find, bid to the
   marriage. Math.22.

   This sense is antiquated, but we have the same word from the Latin, in
   invite, [in and bid.]
